    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Photographic prints made on a gelatin-silver chloride photographic paper introduced commercially in 1867 by the Munich-born chemist Johann Baptist Obernetter. This was considered the first industrial ready-to-use photographic paper print process. Aristotypes are composed of a paper layer, a layer of baryum sulphate in gelatin, and a layer of emulsion containing silver chloride suspended in a binder. The baryta layer made purer whites possible. As this was was a printing-out-paper, aristotypes are exclusively contact prints.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Impresiones fotográficas hechas en papel fotográfico, plata sobre gelatina, el cual crea imágenes de contacto marrón muy detalladas; originalmente se refería al tipo de papel introducido comercialmente en 1868.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Fotografische afdrukken die zijn gemaakt op met gelatine-zilverchloride behandeld fotopapier, waarmee uiterst gedetailleerde bruine contactafdrukken konden worden gemaakt; oorspronkelijk verwijst de term naar het type papier dat in 1868 op de markt verscheen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
